{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.05,0.05,0.43,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40712"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents with a painless swelling under the left side of his jaw. He first noticed this about one month ago and it has been slowly increasing in size (Image). His medical history includes resection of a colonic cancer five years earlier. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine a day. Apart from the firm, well demarcated swelling visible in the photograph, the physical examination is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enlarged submandibular lymph node","Epidermoid cyst","Lipoma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Branchial cyst"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe site of the swelling and the relative rapidity of growth makes the diagnosis of an\u003Cstrong\u003E enlarged submandibular lymph node \u003C/strong\u003Equite reasonable. The patient will require a thorough oropharyngeal examination, looking for a primary site. Fine needle aspiration cytology will also be needed to help define the process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile this clinical picture could be a \u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphic adenoma \u003C/strong\u003Eof the submandibular salivary gland, this is rare. This is the most common benign tumour of the salivary glands, but these tumours are usually found in the parotid gland and only rarely in the submandibular gland. Pleomorphic adenomas do not usually grow at the rate reported by this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a slow-growing, fatty lump usually found in the subcutaneous tissues. Whilst they can be found at any site on the body, most occur on the trunk. They can feel doughy and are not usually as well demarcated as the lesion seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst \u003C/strong\u003Eis a slow-growing, painless lump and usually much smaller than the lesion seen in this patient. Typically there is a punctum at the apex, indicating the opening of the cyst. Inside the cyst may be a yellowish, soft cheese-like, unpleasant-smelling material. These cysts occur as the result blockage of a hair follicle, which allows the cyst to form. They are more common in people who experience acne, as they tend to have more blocked pores.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst is \u003C/strong\u003Ea cystic degeneration within a lymph node and can occur in any cervical lymph node, but typically arises in level 2 or the \u0022tonsillar node\u0022. Branchial cysts usually cause no immediate problem, but they can cause a pressure sensation in the affected area. They are typically not tender. Rarely, however, they can become infected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A painless submental swelling must always raise the possibility of an underlying malignancy."],"references":["Lee JH, Kang HJ, Yoo CW, et al. PLAG1, SOX10, and Myb Expression in Benign and Malignant Salivary Gland Neoplasms. J Pathol Transl Med. 2019 Jan;53(1):23-30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30424592/","Gleave EN, Whittaker JS, Nicholson A. Salivary tumours--experience over thirty years. Clin Otolaryngol Allied Sci. 1979 Aug;4(4):247-57. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/225069/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18815"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18815"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9e2cccb6-49a1-4dce-86c7-52b9d0e913d4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9e2cccb6-49a1-4dce-86c7-52b9d0e913d4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40712"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T22:56:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T22:57:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"740"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55194"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attri